An `async` function ALWAYS returns a Promise. TypeScript automatically wraps the return value:

```typescript
async function greet(): Promise<string> {
  return 'hello'; // TypeScript knows this is Promise<string>
}

// Equivalent to:
function greet(): Promise<string> {
  return Promise.resolve('hello');
}
```

If you write the return type annotation as `Promise<string>`, great. If you omit it, TypeScript infers `Promise<string>` automatically.

If you write `: string` as the return type annotation on an async function — TypeScript will error! The actual return is `Promise<string>`, not `string`.

Similarly, `async function fn() { return; }` returns `Promise<void>`.

`Promise.all` uses TypeScript's tuple inference to preserve per-element types:

```typescript
// TypeScript infers a TUPLE when given array literal:
const [user, posts, settings] = await Promise.all([
  fetchUser(),    // Promise<User>
  fetchPosts(),   // Promise<Post[]>
  fetchSettings() // Promise<Settings>
]);
// user: User, posts: Post[], settings: Settings — all typed!
```

This works because `Promise.all` has multiple overloads for tuples. If you store the array first in a variable, TypeScript may widen it to `(User | Post[] | Settings)[]` — use `as const` or pass the array inline to preserve tuple inference.

`Promise.allSettled` returns `PromiseSettledResult<T>[]` — each item is either `{ status: 'fulfilled', value: T }` or `{ status: 'rejected', reason: any }`.

`T | Promise<T>` (or the more standard `T | PromiseLike<T>`) represents a SYNC-OR-ASYNC value:

```typescript
type MaybePromise<T> = T | Promise<T>;

function loadConfig(source: 'env' | 'file'): MaybePromise<Config> {
  if (source === 'env') return parseEnv(); // synchronous
  return readFile('config.json').then(JSON.parse); // async
}

// Callers that want to always handle async:
const config = await loadConfig('env'); // await on a non-promise just returns the value
```

`await` on a non-Promise value is basically a no-op and returns the value directly, so callers can always safely `await` a `MaybePromise<T>` value. The result type is always `T`.

TypeScript does NOT track what errors functions may throw — the error channel is invisible in the type system. The functional RESULT PATTERN makes it explicit:

```typescript
type Result<T, E = Error> = 
  | { ok: true; value: T }
  | { ok: false; error: E };

async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<Result<User, ApiError>> {
  try {
    const user = await api.get(`/users/${id}`);
    return { ok: true, value: user };
  } catch (e) {
    return { ok: false, error: toApiError(e) };
  }
}

// Callers MUST handle the error case:
const result = await fetchUser('42');
if (result.ok) {
  console.log(result.value.name);
} else {
  console.error(result.error.message);
}
```

Note: catch variable typing — `catch (e)` always gives `e: unknown` (with `useUnknownInCatchVariables: true`). You must narrow it with `instanceof Error` before accessing `.message`.
